## Example 5 — Real-World: Medical Test Probability

A disease affects 1% of the population. A test has 95% accuracy (true positive rate) and a 3% false positive rate. If a person tests positive, what is the probability they have the disease?

### Step 1: Define Events

- $D$: person has disease, $P(D) = 0.01$
- $D'$: person does not have disease, $P(D') = 0.99$
- $T^+$: test is positive
- $P(T^+ \mid D) = 0.95$ (true positive)
- $P(T^+ \mid D') = 0.03$ (false positive)

### Step 2: Compute $P(T^+)$

$$P(T^+) = P(T^+ \mid D) \cdot P(D) + P(T^+ \mid D') \cdot P(D')$$

$$P(T^+) = (0.95)(0.01) + (0.03)(0.99)$$

$$= 0.0095 + 0.0297 = 0.0392$$

### Step 3: Apply Bayes' Theorem (Simplified)

$$P(D \mid T^+) = \frac{P(T^+ \mid D) \cdot P(D)}{P(T^+)} = \frac{0.0095}{0.0392} \approx 0.242$$

### Step 4: Interpret

Even with a positive test, there is only about a **24.2%** chance the person actually has the disease. This is because the false positive rate applied to the large healthy population produces many false alarms.

✅ Answer: $P(\text{disease} \mid \text{positive test}) \approx 24.2\%$

